Items.description: The 2005 Century 21 Home Run Derby was a 2005 Major League Baseball All-Star Game event held at Comerica Park, the home field of the Detroit Tigers on July 11, 2005. The competition had eight competitors as usual and seven were eliminated over the course of three rounds. In honor of the inaugural World Baseball Classic, all the competitors represented their home countries, each representing a different country.

Items.description: A superchoir consisting of three choirs from Windsor, Ontario, sang "O Canada", the Canadian National Anthem. Then, a moment of silence for the victims of the July 7 London bombings, which took place a few days before the game, followed by the Detroit Symphony Orchestra Brass Players' performance of "God Save the Queen", the national anthem of the United Kingdom. Brian McKnight sang The Star-Spangled Banner, the U.S. National Anthem. The colors presentation was by the Camp Grayling color guard, accompanied by University of Toledo ROTC officers who presented the flags in the outfield.

Items.description: Florida rallied over the Atlanta Braves 6-4 Saturday night in a game that was delayed by rain for more than three hours.
Items.vs: Florida Marlins vs. Atlanta Braves

Items.description: Tampa Bay left fielder Damon Hollins lost track of the outs in the seventh inning Saturday and threw a live ball into the stands, helping the Baltimore Orioles beat the Devil Rays 4-3.

Items.description: Pittsburgh 5, Milwaukee 1
Items.vs: Pittsburgh Pirates vs. Milwaukee Brewers

Items.description: Minnesota took advantage of a wild pitch on Jacque Jones' strikeout to defeat the Detroit Tigers 3-0 Saturday night.
Items.vs: Minnesota Twins vs. Detroit Tigers

Items.description: David Wright's two-run homer Saturday night helped the Mets defeat the Colorado Rockies 3-1.
Items.vs: New York Mets vs. Colorado Rockies

Items.description: Garret Anderson, Orlando Cabrera and Juan Rivera homered, and the Angels held off the Texas Rangers 7-6 Saturday night.

Items.vs: Cleveland Indians vs. Chicago White Sox

Items.description: When Florida Marlins manager Jack McKeon told his players Sunday he was calling it quits, they responded with applause and hugs -- and then a comeback win.
Items.vs: Florida Marlins vs. Atlanta Braves

Items.description: Jimmy Rollins stretched his hitting streak to 36 games and scored twice and the Phillies beat the Washington Nationals 9-3 Sunday to complete a three-game sweep -- falling a game short of Houston in the NL wild-card race.
Items.vs: Washington Nationals vs. Philadelphia Phillies

Items.description: Gustavo Chacin extended his team record for rookies with his 13th win, and Eric Hinske homered and drove in three runs as the Toronto Blue Jays ended the season with a 7-2 victory over the woeful Kansas City Royals on Sunday.
Items.vs: Toronto Blue Jays vs. Kansas City Royals

Items.description: Tributes to Mike Piazza were the only thing for Mets fans to cheer about Sunday.
Items.vs: New York Mets vs. Colorado Rockies

Items.description: Rookie Zach Duke won again, pitching the Pittsburgh Pirates past Milwaukee 3-1 Sunday and leaving the Brewers with an 81-81 record.
Items.vs: Pittsburgh Pirates vs. Milwaukee Brewers

Items.description: Reigning World Series MVP Manny Ramirez hit a three-run homer and also threw out Derek Jeter from the outfield on Sunday, and Curt Schilling shut the Yankees down long enough for the Red Sox to beat them 10-1 and clinch the AL wild-card berth.
Items.vs: Boston Red Sox vs. New York Yankees

Items.description: Roy Oswalt became the first pitcher since 2001-02 with consecutive 20-win seasons, throwing six innings and driving in a run Sunday in a 6-4 victory over the Chicago Cubs to clinch the NL wild-card spot for the Astros.
Items.vs: Houston Astros vs. Chicago Cubs

Items.description: The Los Angeles Angels clinched home-field advantage for the first round the AL playoffs, closing out the regular season by beating Texas 7-4 Sunday behind Juan Rivera's three-run homer.

Items.description: Turning in one last stellar start in his long-shot Cy Young Award bid, Johan Santana gave up three hits in seven innings and led the Twins past the Detroit Tigers 6-4 in Sunday's season finale.

Items.description: The Cardinals posted their 100th victory by rallying past Cincinnati 7-5 Sunday in the last regular-season game at Busch Stadium.
Items.vs: St. Louis Cardinals vs. Cincinnati Reds

Items.description: Adam Eaton was brilliant in his final playoff tuneup, striking out a season-high 11 and holding Los Angeles to one hit in seven scoreless innings as the NL West champion Padres beat the Dodgers 3-1 on Sunday to finish 82-80 (.506).
Items.vs: San Diego Padres vs. Los Angeles Dodgers

Items.description: The San Francisco Giants snapped a five-game skid with a 3-1 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks on Sunday.
